{"ts": "2026-06-07T11:28:39.000Z", "event": "planner", "msg": "L3 task decomposition", "agent": "planner-l3", "tokens_in": 745, "tokens_out": 1580, "elapsed_ms": 18648, "model": "qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507", "prompt": "You are the Level 3 Planner. Decompose the user task into subtasks for dynamic agent creation.\n\nOutput JSON:\n{{\n  \"subtasks\": [\n    {{\"task_id\": \"short-name\", \"description\": \"What this worker must produce — ALWAYS include the user's exact request at the top\"}}\n  ]\n}}\n\n## Critical Rules\n- Each subtask description MUST begin with \"USER REQUEST: <exact user task text>\" — this prevents worker hallucination\n- Each subtask must be focused, self-contained, with explicit output file names\n- Never create duplicate task_ids — each worker name must be unique\n- For simple tasks, 3-4 subtasks; for complex tasks, 4-6\n- Always include a \"tester\" as the FINAL subtask — running test_report.json validation\n- Specify exact file names each worker must produce (e.g. \"Write to styles.css\", \"Write to app.js\")\n- Workers receive NO prior context beyond their subtask description — be thorough in the description\n- Output ONLY the JSON object — no markdown fences, no extra text\n\n## Specialty\nfrontend\n\n## User Request\nBuild a fully functional task management web app called \"Taskr\" delivered as index.html, style.css, and app.js.\n\nFeatures required:\n- Add, edit, delete tasks\n- Mark tasks as complete (with visual strike-through)\n- Filter by status (all / active / completed)\n- Persist tasks to localStorage\n- Drag to reorder tasks\n- Responsive on mobile and desktop\n\nAfter the initial build, a Tester will run a checklist against the app and report all failures. The team must fix every reported failure and resubmit. This cycle repeats until the Tester reports a full pass or 3 iterations are exhausted.\n\nDeliver the final version plus a report.md documenting what the Tester found in each round and what was fixed.\n\nFor frontend tasks, you MUST follow these constraints:\n- Always include a final \"integration\" subtask that merges all content/fragments into index.html\n- Always include a \"tester\" subtask as the VERY LAST subtask\n- Good decomposition: [content, html_structure, styling, interactivity, integration, tester]\n- Bad decomposition: [hero_builder, features_builder, cta_builder] — these create standalone pages\n- Each subtask description MUST include the user's verbatim request text at the top\n- Section subtasks produce content fragments into shared files, NOT standalone HTML files\n- The pipeline produces ONE web page: index.html + styles.css + app.js\n\n## CSS-HTML Coordination\n- The HTML worker MUST add semantic CSS classes to every major section (class=\"hero\", class=\"features\", class=\"cta\", class=\"footer\" etc.)\n- The styling worker's subtask MUST say: \"read_file('index.html') FIRST. Write CSS selectors matching the EXACT classes/IDs/elements found in index.html. Do NOT invent new class names.\"\n- The integration subtask MUST include: \"1) read index.html to see classes used, 2) read content.txt for real text, 3) read styles.css to see which classes need to exist, 4) write_file('index.html') with content injected AND missing CSS classes added, 5) read_file('index.html') to verify.\"\n\n## Token Efficiency\n- Each worker≈100K token budget limit for the entire pipeline, plan your decomposition and worker complexity accordingly\n- Avoid micro-workers that do trivial tasks — combine related work into fewer, more substantial workers\n- The CSS/styling worker should NOT call validate_css more than 3 times total", "meta": {}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T11:29:04.000Z", "event": "agent_creator", "msg": "Agent Creator L3 — generating workers", "agent": "agent-creator-l3", "tokens_in": 2549, "tokens_out": 2646, "elapsed_ms": 25251, "model": "qwen/qwen3-235b-a22b-2507", "prompt": "You are the Advanced Agent Creator (Level 3 — Fully Autonomous). Your role: create worker agents from scratch with custom system instructions, tools, and dynamic code tools.\n\n## Available Tools\nThe tool menu for this specialty:\n[\"read_file\", \"write_file\", \"list_files\", \"run_command\", \"render_html_screenshot\", \"render_html_file_screenshot\", \"validate_html\", \"validate_css\", \"read_image\", \"generate_image\"]\n\n## Task Plan\nThe planner has decomposed the task into subtasks:\n{\n  \"subtasks\": [\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"content\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build a fully functional task management web app called \\\"Taskr\\\" delivered as index.html, style.css, and app.js.\\n\\nFeatures required:\\n- Add, edit, delete tasks\\n- Mark tasks as complete (with visual strike-through)\\n- Filter by status (all / active / completed)\\n- Persist tasks to localStorage\\n- Drag to reorder tasks\\n- Responsive on mobile and desktop\\n\\nAfter the initial build, a Tester will run a checklist against the app and report all failures. The team must fix every reported failure and resubmit. This cycle repeats until the Tester reports a full pass or 3 iterations are exhausted.\\n\\nDeliver the final version plus a report.md documenting what the Tester found in each round and what was fixed.\\n\\nProduce a content plan for the app interface: task list layout, button labels, placeholder text, filter options, and any instructional text. Write to content.txt. Include semantic class names for major UI components: class=\\\"task-list\\\", class=\\\"task-item\\\", class=\\\"task-input\\\", class=\\\"filter-controls\\\", class=\\\"app-header\\\", etc. These will be used by HTML and CSS workers.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"html_structure\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build a fully functional task management web app called \\\"Taskr\\\" delivered as index.html, style.css, and app.js.\\n\\nFeatures required:\\n- Add, edit, delete tasks\\n- Mark tasks as complete (with visual strike-through)\\n- Filter by status (all / active / completed)\\n- Persist tasks to localStorage\\n- Drag to reorder tasks\\n- Responsive on mobile and desktop\\n\\nAfter the initial build, a Tester will run a checklist against the app and report all failures. The team must fix every reported failure and resubmit. This cycle repeats until the Tester reports a full pass or 3 iterations are exhausted.\\n\\nDeliver the final version plus a report.md documenting what the Tester found in each round and what was fixed.\\n\\nCreate a valid HTML5 structure for index.html. Use semantic elements (header, main, footer, section). Include all required UI sections: app header, task input area, task list container, filter controls. Add the exact CSS classes from content.txt (e.g. class=\\\"task-list\\\", class=\\\"task-input\\\"). Include links to style.css and app.js. Do NOT include inline styles or scripts. Write to index.html.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"styling\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build a fully functional task management web app called \\\"Taskr\\\" delivered as index.html, style.css, and app.js.\\n\\nFeatures required:\\n- Add, edit, delete tasks\\n- Mark tasks as complete (with visual strike-through)\\n- Filter by status (all / active / completed)\\n- Persist tasks to localStorage\\n- Drag to reorder tasks\\n- Responsive on mobile and desktop\\n\\nAfter the initial build, a Tester will run a checklist against the app and report all failures. The team must fix every reported failure and resubmit. This cycle repeats until the Tester reports a full pass or 3 iterations are exhausted.\\n\\nDeliver the final version plus a report.md documenting what the Tester found in each round and what was fixed.\\n\\nread_file('index.html') FIRST. Write CSS selectors matching the EXACT classes/IDs/elements found in index.html. Do NOT invent new class names. Style the app to be clean, modern, and fully responsive. Ensure mobile touch targets are adequate. Implement visual strike-through for completed tasks. Use CSS to support drag-and-drop UX (e.g. cursor feedback). Write to style.css. Validate CSS no more than 3 times.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"interactivity\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build a fully functional task management web app called \\\"Taskr\\\" delivered as index.html, style.css, and app.js.\\n\\nFeatures required:\\n- Add, edit, delete tasks\\n- Mark tasks as complete (with visual strike-through)\\n- Filter by status (all / active / completed)\\n- Persist tasks to localStorage\\n- Drag to reorder tasks\\n- Responsive on mobile and desktop\\n\\nAfter the initial build, a Tester will run a checklist against the app and report all failures. The team must fix every reported failure and resubmit. This cycle repeats until the Tester reports a full pass or 3 iterations are exhausted.\\n\\nDeliver the final version plus a report.md documenting what the Tester found in each round and what was fixed.\\n\\nImplement full JavaScript interactivity in app.js: task addition, editing, deletion, toggle completion with strike-through, filtering (all/active/completed), drag-and-drop reordering with visual feedback, and localStorage persistence (save on change, load on start). Use event delegation where appropriate. Ensure mobile touch compatibility for drag. Write to app.js.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"integration\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build a fully functional task management web app called \\\"Taskr\\\" delivered as index.html, style.css, and app.js.\\n\\nFeatures required:\\n- Add, edit, delete tasks\\n- Mark tasks as complete (with visual strike-through)\\n- Filter by status (all / active / completed)\\n- Persist tasks to localStorage\\n- Drag to reorder tasks\\n- Responsive on mobile and desktop\\n\\nAfter the initial build, a Tester will run a checklist against the app and report all failures. The team must fix every reported failure and resubmit. This cycle repeats until the Tester reports a full pass or 3 iterations are exhausted.\\n\\nDeliver the final version plus a report.md documenting what the Tester found in each round and what was fixed.\\n\\n1) read index.html to see classes used, 2) read content.txt for real text, 3) read styles.css to see which classes need to exist, 4) write_file('index.html') with content injected AND missing CSS classes added, 5) read_file('index.html') to verify. Ensure all assets are correctly linked and the app is self-contained in index.html, style.css, and app.js.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"task_id\": \"tester\",\n      \"description\": \"USER REQUEST: Build a fully functional task management web app called \\\"Taskr\\\" delivered as index.html, style.css, and app.js.\\n\\nFeatures required:\\n- Add, edit, delete tasks\\n- Mark tasks as complete (with visual strike-through)\\n- Filter by status (all / active / completed)\\n- Persist tasks to localStorage\\n- Drag to reorder tasks\\n- Responsive on mobile and desktop\\n\\nAfter the initial build, a Tester will run a checklist against the app and report all failures. The team must fix every reported failure and resubmit. This cycle repeats until the Tester reports a full pass or 3 iterations are exhausted.\\n\\nDeliver the final version plus a report.md documenting what the Tester found in each round and what was fixed.\\n\\nRun automated and manual checks on index.html, style.css, and app.js. Validate all features: add/edit/delete, completion toggle, filtering, localStorage persistence, drag-to-reorder, mobile responsiveness. Generate test_report.json with pass/fail for each item. If failures exist, trigger a new iteration with fixes. After up to 3 iterations, compile final report.md summarizing findings and fixes per round. Final output must include working app files and report.md.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n\n## Specialty-Specific Architecture Constraints\nFor FRONTEND specialty:\n- One worker MUST produce index.html as the canonical entry page\n- All CSS lives in ONE shared styles.css file. All JavaScript in ONE shared app.js file.\n- Workers write SECTIONS INTO these shared files — they do NOT create standalone HTML pages.\n- If you create section-specific workers (hero, features, cta),\n  the pipeline MUST end with an integrator that merges all sections\n  into a single index.html with linked styles.css and app.js.\n- Never design a pipeline where each worker produces its own standalone HTML page.\n- The user expects ONE complete web page, not a collection of separate HTML files.\n\n## HTML-CSS Coordination (CRITICAL — prevents broken pages)\nEvery CSS worker system_prompt MUST include:\n- 'iCRITICAL: read_file(\"index.html\") FIRST before writing any CSS. Your selectors MUST match actual elements/classes/IDs in the HTML.'\n- 'Use the SAME class naming convention as the HTML. If HTML uses class=\"hero\", write .hero {{}}. Never invent new class names.'\nEvery HTML worker system_prompt MUST include:\n- 'Add semantic CSS classes to ALL major sections: class=\"header\", class=\"hero\", class=\"features\", class=\"cta\", class=\"footer\" etc.'\n- 'Use class selectors (not just bare element tags) so the CSS worker can target them reliably.'\nEvery integrator system_prompt MUST include:\n- '1. read_file(\"index.html\") to see current HTML structure and classes'\n- '2. Inject real content from content.txt INTO the existing HTML — do NOT rewrite the HTML from scratch'\n- '3. Add any missing CSS classes to elements that the stylesheet targets'\n- '4. write_file(\"index.html\", ...) to save — NEVER skip this step'\n- '5. read_file(\"index.html\") to verify the merge succeeded'\n\n## Conversation History & Memory Protocol (MUST include in every worker prompt)\nEvery worker's system_prompt MUST include:\n- 'Your conversation history is LIMITED. The LLM only sees the last 3 tool-call turns.'\n- 'Use WORKSPACE FILES as your persistent memory — always read_file() at start of iteration.'\n- 'Do NOT re-read unchanged files — use list_files to verify existence instead.'\n- 'Tool results from read_file are truncated to 3000 chars and cached.'\n- 'After completing, write exactly ONE final output file and STOP. Do not iterate needlessly.'\n\n\n## Your Job\nFor EACH subtask in the plan:\n1. WRITE a custom system_prompt from scratch — give the worker clear role, boundaries, and workflow\n2. SELECT tools from the available tool menu that the worker needs\n3. If available tools are insufficient, CREATE dynamic_tools as Python code strings\n4. Optionally create inline_skills as text fragments (not loaded from files)\n\n## Dynamic Tools (Python code strings)\nDynamic tools are Python functions the worker can call. Write them as complete, executable code strings.\nExample:\n  \"dynamic_tools\": [{\"name\": \"fetch_api\", \"code\": \"import httpx\\nasync def fetch_api(url):\\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as c:\\n        return (await c.get(url)).text\", \"description\": \"Fetch data from an API\"}]\n\n## Rules\n- Output ONLY valid JSON — no markdown fences, no extra text\n- worker_name: give each worker a unique short name (e.g. \"scraper\", \"analyzer\", \"validator\")\n- system_prompt: must be detailed — role, boundaries, tools to use, workflow, output format\n- tool_names: only from the available tool menu\n- dynamic_tools: list of {name, code, description} — only create if needed\n- inline_skills: list of prompt fragments for worker knowledge\n\n## Output Format\n{\n  \"workers\": [\n    {\n      \"worker_name\": \"unique_name\",\n      \"system_prompt\": \"Full custom system instructions\",\n      \"tool_names\": [\"tool1\", \"tool2\"],\n      \"dynamic_tools\": [{\"name\": \".\", \"code\": \".\", \"description\": \".\"}],\n      \"inline_skills\": [\"Skill fragment text...\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "meta": {}}
