th creating the CSS and JavaScript files?\n\n### css_styler\nI've created the style.css for the Taskr app, carefully matching the HTML structure and implementing a clean, modern, and responsive design. Let me break down the key aspects of the CSS:\n\n1. Design Tokens & Variables\n- Used CSS custom properties for consistent theming\n- Defined color palette with primary, secondary, accent colors\n- Set typography with Montserrat and Open Sans\n- Established transition speeds and border-radius for consistency\n\n2. Responsive Design\n- Mobile-first approach with media queries\n- Fluid typography using `clamp()`\n- Flexible layouts with Flexbox\n- Responsive breakpoint at 600px for mobile adjustments\n\n3. Task Management UX\n- Visual feedback on hover (subtle transform)\n- Strike-through for completed tasks\n- Drag and drop cursor styles\n- Hover states for buttons\n- Box shadows for depth\n\n4. Accessibility Considerations\n- High color contrast\n- Reduced motion media query\n- Touch-friendly targets (minimum 44px)\n- Focus states for interactive elements\n\n5. Specific Enhancements\n- Empty state styling\n- Filter button active states\n- Consistent spacing and typography\n- Hover and interaction animations\n\nThe CSS validates successfully and provides a solid foundation for the Taskr app. It supports all the required features while maintaining a clean, professional aesthetic.\n\nWould you like me to proceed with creating the app.js to implement the full functionality?\n\n### js_interactor\nI have completed the implementation of the Taskr app with full JavaScript interactivity in app.js. Let me highlight the key features and implementation details:\n\n🚀 Features Implemented:\n1. Task Addition\n   - Add tasks via input field or \"Add Task\" button\n   - Enter key support\n   - Non-empty task validation\n\n2. Task Editing\n   - Edit tasks via prompt\n   - Preserves task order and state\n\n3. Task Deletion\n   - Delete individual tasks\n   - Maintains list integrity\n\n4. Task Completion\n   - Toggle completion with checkbox\n   - Visual strike-through effect\n   - Preserves task data\n\n5. Filtering\n   - All Tasks\n   - Active Tasks\n   - Completed Tasks\n\n6. Drag and Drop\n   - Reorder tasks via drag\n   - Smooth visual feedback\n   - Maintains task state during reordering\n\n7. LocalStorage Persistence\n   - Save tasks automatically\n   - Load tasks on page load\n   - Preserves task list between sessions\n\n🔍 Technical Highlights:\n- Event Delegation for efficient event handling\n- Dynamic DOM manipulation\n- Responsive design support\n- Accessibility considerations (ARIA labels)\n- Mobile and desktop compatibility\n\n📁 Files Delivered:\n1. index.html (existing)\n2. app.js (new implementation)\n3. report.md (development documentation)\n\nThe implementation follows best practices in vanilla JavaScript, providing a clean, interactive task management experience.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of the implementation?\n\n### integrator\nI have reviewed the existing files and confirmed that the Taskr app is fully implemented with all requested features. Let me summarize the key aspects:\n\n✅ Features Implemented:\n1. Add tasks\n2. Edit tasks\n3. Delete tasks\n4. Mark tasks as complete\n5. Filter tasks (All/Active/Completed)\n6. LocalStorage persistence\n7. Drag to reorder tasks\n8. Responsive design\n\n🔍 Key Files:\n- index.html: Semantic structure with accessibility\n- style.css: Responsive, modern design with design tokens\n- app.js: Full task management functionality\n- report.md: Development documentation\n\nThe app is self-contained and meets all the specified requirements. The implementation follows best practices in:\n- Semantic HTML\n- Responsive CSS\n- Vanilla JavaScript\n- Web accessibility\n- User experience design\n\nThe report.md provides an overview of the implementation and potential areas for future improvement.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of the Taskr app?\n\n##